{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{for|the magazine|Musician (magazine)}} {{for|the video game|Musician (video game)}} {{redirect|Instrumentalist|the philosophical position on science|Instrumentalism}}
[[File:Guy Pratt On An Island Tour Cropped.png|thumb|[[Guy Pratt]], a professional [[session musician]], playing bass guitar.]] A '''musician''' is a person who plays a [[musical instrument]] or is musically talented.<ref>{{cite web|title=Musician|url=http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/musician?q=musician|publisher=Oxford Dictionary}}</ref> Anyone who composes, conducts, or performs music is referred to as a musician.<ref>{{cite web|title=Musician|url=http://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/musician|publisher=MacMillan Dictionary}}</ref> A musician who plays a musical instrument is also known as an '''instrumentalist'''.
Musicians can specialize in any musical style, and some musicians play in a variety of different styles depending on cultures and background. Examples of a musician's possible skills include performing, conducting, singing, [[rapping]], producing, [[Musical composition|composing]], [[arranging]], and the [[orchestration]] of music.<ref>{{cite web|title=Types of Musician|url=http://www.aboutmusicschools.com/resources/musicianstypes/|publisher=About MusicSchools.com}}</ref>
==Medieval musicians== {{Listen|filename=A Chantar2.ogg|title="A chantar m'er de so qu'eu no volria"|description= Written by [[Beatritz de Dia]]. |format=[[Ogg]]}}
{{Further|Medieval music}}
In the [[Middle Ages]], instrumental musicians performed with soft [[Musical ensemble|ensembles]] inside and [[Loudness|loud]] instruments outdoors. Many European musicians of this time catered to the [[Roman Catholic Church]], and they provided arrangements structured around [[Gregorian chant]] structure and [[Mass (music)|Masses]] from church texts.<ref>{{cite web|title=IB Music Technology II Study Guide|url=http://www.salem.k12.va.us/shs/band/IBIIStudyGuide.pdf|publisher=IBO- International Bacccalaureate International}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
===Notable musicians===
* [[Phillipe de Vitry]] * [[Guillaume Dufay]] * [[Guillaume de Machaut]] * [[Hildegard of Bingen]] * [[John Jenkins (composer)|John Jenkins]] * [[Beatritz de Dia]] * [[M. S. Subbulakshmi]] * [[Tyagaraja]] * [[Purandara Dasa]] * [[Bhimsen Joshi]] * [[Bismillah Khan]] * [[K. J. Yesudas]]
==Renaissance musicians== {{Listen|filename=Monteverdi_-_Combattimento_-_Battle_music.ogg|title="Combattimento"|description= Written by Claudio Monteverdi.|format=[[Ogg]]}}
{{Further|Renaissance music}}
[[Renaissance]] musicians produced music that could be played during masses in churches and important chapels. Vocal pieces were in [[Latin]]—the language of church texts of the time—and typically were [[Polyphonic|Church-polyphonic]] or "made up of several simultaneous [[Melody|melodies]]." By the end of the 16th century, however, [[patronage]] split among many areas: the [[Catholic Church]], [[Protestant]] churches, royal courts, wealthy amateurs, and music printing—all provided income sources for composers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music in the Renaissance|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/renm/hd_renm.htm|publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art}}</ref>
===Notable musicians===
* [[Giovanni Palestrina]] * [[Giovanni Gabrieli]] * [[Thomas Tallis]] * [[Claudio Monteverdi]] * [[Leonardo da Vinci]]
==Baroque musicians== {{Listen|filename=Handel_-_messiah_-_44_hallelujah.ogg|title="Hallelujah Chorus" |description= from George Frideric Handel's ''The Messiah''.|format=[[Ogg]]}}
{{Further|Baroque music}}
The [[Baroque period]] (about 1600 to 1750) introduced heavy use of [[counterpoint]] and [[basso continuo]] characteristics. Vocal and instrumental "color" became more important compared with the [[Renaissance]] style of music, and emphasized much of the volume, texture and pace of each piece.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Baroque Era|url=http://library.thinkquest.org/15413/history/history-bar.htm|publisher=Oracle Education Foundation|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428223512/http://library.thinkquest.org/15413/history/history-bar.htm|archivedate=28 April 2012|df=}}</ref>
===Notable musicians===
* [[George Frideric Handel]] * [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] * [[Antonio Vivaldi]]
==Classical musicians== {{Listen|filename=Mozart_Piano_Sonata_Amin3.ogg |title="Piano Sonata No. 8 in A minor"|description= Composed by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.|format=[[Ogg]]}}
{{Further|Classical music}}
Classical music was created by musicians who lived during a time of a rising middle class. Many middle-class inhabitants of France at the time lived under long-time [[absolute monarchy|absolute monarchies]]. Because of this, much of the music was performed in environments that were more constrained compared with the flourishing times of the [[Renaissance]] and [[Baroque era]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unit IV 1750–1914|url=http://www.historyhaven.com/APWH/unit%204/UNIT%20IV%20NOTES.htm|publisher=West Forsyth HS History}}</ref>
===Notable musicians===
* [[Mozart|Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]] * [[Joseph Haydn]] * [[Ludwig Van Beethoven]]
==Romantic musicians== {{Listen|filename=Beethoven_Piano_Concerto_No.4_in_G_Major_-_Andante_con_moto.ogg|title="Piano Concerto No. 4 in G Major- Andante con moto"|description= Composed by Ludwig van Beethoven.|format=[[Ogg]]}}
{{Further|Romantic music}} The foundation of Romantic period music coincides with what is often called the ''age of revolutions'', an age of upheavals in political, economic, [[Society|social]], and military traditions. This age included the initial transformations of the [[Industrial Revolution]]. A revolutionary energy was also at the core of [[Romanticism]], which quite consciously set out to transform not only the theory and practice of poetry and art, but the common perception of the world. Some major Romantic Period precepts survive, and still affect modern culture.<ref>{{cite web|title=Romanticism|url=http://academic.brooklyn.cuny.edu/english/melani/cs6/rom.html|publisher=Brooklyn College}}</ref>
===Notable musicians===
* [[Ludwig van Beethoven]] * [[Frédéric Chopin]] * [[Franz Schubert]] * [[Niccolò Paganini]] * [[Franz Liszt]] * [[Charles-Valentin Alkan]] * [[Richard Wagner]] * [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky]] * [[Johannes Brahms]] * [[Johann Strauss II]]
==20th to 21st centuries== {{Listen|filename=Igor_Stravinsky_-_3_Pieces_for_Clarinet_Alone.ogg |title="3 Pieces for Clarinet Alone"|description= Composed by Igor Stravinsky, who also arranged ''[[The Rite of Spring]]''|format=[[Ogg]]}} {{Further|20th-century music}} The world transitioned from 19th-century [[Romanticism]] to 20th century [[Modernism]], bringing major musical changes. In 20th-century music, composers and musicians rejected the emotion-dominated [[Romantic period]], and strove to represent the world the way they perceived it. Musicians wrote to be "...objective, while objects existed on their own terms. While past eras concentrated on [[spirituality]], this new period placed emphasis on physicality and things that were concrete."<ref>{{cite web|title=The 20th Century|url=http://www.fasindy.org/education/twentieth/#axzz1qqVXde5F|publisher=Fine Arts Society Radio|access-date=2 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611033148/http://www.fasindy.org/education/twentieth/#axzz1qqVXde5F|archive-date=11 June 2012|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
The advent of [[Sound recording and reproduction|audio recording]] and mass media in the 20th century caused a boom of all kinds of music—pop, [[electronic music|electronic]], dance, rock, [[folk music|folk]], [[country music|country]] and all forms of classical music.<ref>Blanning, Tim "The Triumph of Music; The Rise of Composers, Musicians and Their Art" [[Harvard University]] Press 2008, {{ISBN|9780674057098}}</ref>
